Pill-esophagitis caused by nonsteroidal antiinflammatory drugs.
 A case of meclofenamate-induced pill-esophagitis is reported, and the relevant literature is reviewed.
 The role of posture, amount of fluid chaser, esophageal obstruction or dysmotility, drug formulation, physical and chemical properties of the drug, and concomitant ingestion of alcohol, as well as the diagnosis and management of such cases, are discussed.
